						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Senegal-to-establish-centre-of-excellence" title="Senegal to establish centre of excellence " alt="link">Senegal to establish centre of excellence </a></h2>

	
					<p> Plans are underway for the establishment of a centre of excellence in biotechnology, agriculture, physics, water and nanotechnology in Senegal. Science minister Yaye Kene Gassama Dia said the government has already allocated US$6.24 million and 500 hectares of land for the establishment of the centre. She said they would be looking for additional funding from the African Development Bank and the Islamic Bank of Development to ensure the successful implementation of the project. The Islamic Bank of Development has so far agreed to provide US$300,000 as seed money for the project. Dia also said that said her government was working on increasing budgetary allocations to science by 25% to enable the country to meet the 1% of GDP target set by the African Union. At present, Senegal’s science allocation stands at 0.5%.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Senegal-to-establish-centre-of-excellence">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/West-African-rice-farmers-explore-alternatives-to-cheap-dangerous-insecticides" title="West African rice farmers explore alternatives to cheap, dangerous insecticides" alt="link">West African rice farmers explore alternatives to cheap, dangerous insecticides</a></h2>

	
					<p> Farmer-to-farmer training and on-farm research grow local adapted knowledge of biologically based integrated pest management that embraces biodiversity, careful observation and beneficial insects.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/West-African-rice-farmers-explore-alternatives-to-cheap-dangerous-insecticides">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/33-African-states-lack-science-ministries" title="33 African states lack science ministries" alt="link">33 African states lack science ministries</a></h2>

	
					<p> Only 20 out of Africa’s 53 countries have set up science ministries, a situation that is impacting negatively on the continent’s ability to effectively reduce poverty, according to an official from the UN Economic Commission for Africa (Uneca). The chief of science in Uneca’s ICT, science and technology division, Alex Tindimubona, said that the33 countries are ‘still stuck with commissions or apex bodies that do are not strong enough to negotiate for policies favouring science in cabinet’. ‘It is related to how science, technology and innovations (STI) is viewed at strategies levels. Many countries have not come up to say how they want to transform their societies and economies. If they did that they would see that they need STI,’ he said in an exclusive interview.  A July report from UNCTAD identified a lack of innovation as one of the main contributory factors to poverty in least developed countries. It said that least developed countries have to take innovation seriously if they are to reduce poverty. But, for Africa, this may be long in coming and the goal to allocate one percent of GNP to science by 2015 may be missed without ministerial structures to push the sector into the forefront of development, Tindimubona said. ‘Ministries help build a bigger mandate and capacity to introduce science and technology. Without [a ministry of science and technology] no country can have an impact to introduce science into development.’</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/33-African-states-lack-science-ministries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Global-food-crisis-looms-as-climate-change-and-population-growth-strip-fertile-land" title="Global food crisis looms as climate change and population growth strip fertile land " alt="link">Global food crisis looms as climate change and population growth strip fertile land </a></h2>

	
					<p> Researchers from around the world convened at a recent UN-backed forum in Iceland on sustainable development, to address the UN’s millennium development goals to halve hunger and extreme poverty by 2015. The experts said that to keep up with the growth in human population, more food will have to be produced worldwide over the next 50 years than has been produced during the past 10,000 years combined. But in many countries a combination of poor farming practices and deforestation will be exacerbated by climate change to steadily degrade soil fertility, leaving vast areas unsuitable for crops or grazing. The experts called on countries to impose strict farming guidelines to ensure that soils are not degraded so badly they cannot recover. Approximately 40% of the world’s agricultural land is seriously degraded, estimates indicate. Among the worst affected regions are Central America, where 75% of land is infertile, Africa, where a fifth of soil is degraded, and Asia, where 11% is unsuitable for farming. The UN Millennium Ecosystem Assessment ranked land degradation among the world’s greatest environmental challenges, saying that it destabilizing societies, endangering food security, and increasing poverty.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Global-food-crisis-looms-as-climate-change-and-population-growth-strip-fertile-land">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Science-tech-needed-to-lead-Africa-s-development" title="Science, tech needed to lead Africa’s development" alt="link">Science, tech needed to lead Africa’s development</a></h2>

	
					<p> South African Deputy President Phumzile Mlambo-Ngcuka says science and technology should not be viewed as ‘elitist’ but rather as sectors whose growth can spearhead Africa’s development. The Deputy President was addressing the first AU conference of African Women in Science and Technology. ‘We need to change the structural obstacles, which continue to hinder the development of science and technology for the benefit of the poor. We need to overcome barriers that continue to exclude girl children and women from the study of science and technology,’ she said. The women attending the conference discussed how best they can actively participate in science and technology initiatives, and worked towards developing programmes that will encourage more women to pursue careers in these fields. ‘If we wish to change this perception we need to firstly communicate in ways which makes these subjects attractive. Ms Mlambo-Ngcuka explained that there are a small number of female researchers, constituting an estimated 29% of researchers in Africa, according to statistics by UNESCO. She acknowledged that there is a growing, common understanding in Africa that women’s education, equality and empowerment are vital to ensuring an integrated, developed, prosperous and peaceful continent.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Science-tech-needed-to-lead-Africa-s-development">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Innovative-fish-farming-project-for-HIV-affected-African-families" title="Innovative fish farming project for HIV-affected African families " alt="link">Innovative fish farming project for HIV-affected African families </a></h2>

	
					<p> Scientists have reported that an innovative project to encourage fish farming among families affected by HIV/AIDS in Malawi has doubled the income for 1200 households and greatly increased fish and vegetable consumption among rural communities. The findings were released in a review of a multi-year initiative by the WorldFish Center and World Vision to promote aquaculture among ‘vulnerable populations’ in Malawi. The two organizations have worked extensively throughout Malawi, a country of 12.1 million people that has been devastated by AIDS, encouraging farming families headed by women and orphans to adopt a practice known as integrated agriculture-aquaculture. The project assists farmers by digging small, rain-fed ponds of about 20 x 10 meters, which they use to raise fish such as tilapia. Farm and kitchen waste serves as food for the fish, and the labor requirements are not intensive – children and the elderly can assist – so the ponds are easy to manage for households affected by AIDS.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Innovative-fish-farming-project-for-HIV-affected-African-families">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Can-technology-save-Africa" title="Can technology save Africa?" alt="link">Can technology save Africa?</a></h2>

	
					<p> Jinka, in southern Ethiopia, may seem like a backwater, but it’s at the forefront of a trend sweeping the continent, one that just might rescue Africa’s struggling education systems. The new Jinka high school has a sparkling new computer lab and a gas-powered generator that runs the 42-inch plasma-screen TVs mounted at the front of a classroom. Every day, these screens broadcast lessons piped in from South Africa. The school is part of a $100 million project supported by UNESCO, the World Bank and corporations like Cisco Systems. There are now 458 such schools around the country. Addis Ababa hopes they will help it compensate for extremely scarce resources. No matter that the TV tutorials are all in English and therefore hard for some students to follow. As Africa strives to pull itself out of poverty, more and more countries are looking to technology to give them a leg up. The goal, supported by the UN and NEPAD, is to get the continent IT-ready by next year, when a fiber-optic cable running alongside the east coast is scheduled for completion, bringing broadband access to 22 nations. NEPAD has an ‘e-schools’ initiative that aims (optimistically) to wire all 600,000 African high schools by the time the cable is up and running. But the moves have sparked a big debate over whether it makes sense to spend money on technology before teachers and textbooks.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Can-technology-save-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/South-Africa-helps-Ghana-to-prevent-post-harvest-loss-of-fruits" title="South Africa helps Ghana to prevent post-harvest loss of fruits" alt="link">South Africa helps Ghana to prevent post-harvest loss of fruits</a></h2>

	
					<p> Nampak of South Africa and the Woodstock Institute for Science and Service to Humanity is working with the Institute of Packaging, Ghana to develop a system of preserving and packaging fresh plantain, tomatoes and mangoes in a bid to reduce post-harvest losses. Due to lack of modern methods and technology of preserving food crops in Ghana, many fruits, vegetables and tubers rot after investing. The system being developed will help the export and packaging industries store and package several perishable agricultural products. The IOPG has also signed a Memorandum of Understanding with Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology to establish a School of Packaging to train and certify professionals in the packaging industry in order to boost the industry, export and agriculture. It is estimated that global packaging market is worth $500 billion every year and all types of packaging constitute between about 0.5–2.6% of GDP of countries.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/South-Africa-helps-Ghana-to-prevent-post-harvest-loss-of-fruits">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Nigeria-UNESCO-collaborate-on-science-foundation" title="Nigeria, UNESCO collaborate on science foundation" alt="link">Nigeria, UNESCO collaborate on science foundation</a></h2>

	
					<p> 
The Federal Government and the UNESCO are collaborating on a project that will see to the emergence of a N5 billion Science Foundation for the country. The collaboration will also entail the establishment of six world trust universities and centres of excellence as well as establishment of high technology business zones to attract investments to the 6-geopolitical zones of Nigeria. The project, which also involves the Government of Japan, is funded at a cost of $2.5m, and has reached an advanced stage with three proposals already on the drawing board. The body is committed to support Nigeria's development in line with her vision to be one of top ten economies by the year 2020.Source: This Day (Lagos), 13 August 2007 </p>
							<p><span class="date">24/08/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Nigeria-UNESCO-collaborate-on-science-foundation">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Seminar-discusses-sustainable-biofuel-development-in-Africa" title="Seminar discusses sustainable biofuel development in Africa" alt="link">Seminar discusses sustainable biofuel development in Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p> 
The first High-level Biofuels Seminar in Africa, which met in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, from 30 July to 1 August 2007, has developed an Action Plan for Biofuels Development in Africa. The Action Plan was annexed to the Addis Ababa Declaration on Sustainable Biofuels Development in Africa, which calls for, inter alia: developing enabling policy and regulatory frameworks; participating in global sustainability discussions; formulating guiding principles on biofuels to enhance Africa’s competitiveness; and minimizing the risks of biofuels development for small-scale producers. It further calls for the engagement of development partners to enable North-South and South-South cooperation, urges the engagement of public financing institutions to support biofuels projects, and proposes the establishment of a forum to promote access to biofuels information and knowledge.Source: IISD Reporting Services, August 2007 </p>
							<p><span class="date">24/08/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Seminar-discusses-sustainable-biofuel-development-in-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
